    <stitle>INTERNATIONAL AIR SUSPENSION WITH TAPERED LEAF SPRINGS - HEIGHT CONTROL VALVE</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>HEIGHT CONTROL VALVE</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="2">
            <title>DESCRIPTION</title>
            <para>The height control valve (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0300103">Figure 3</hotlnk>) is the brain of the air suspension and is sensitive to
                height. When properly adjusted it will provide and maintain ride height.
            </para>
            <figure id="f0300103" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0300103" filename="../figg03/G0300103.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="432px"/>
                <caption>Figure 3. Height Control Valve System Components</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. TO AIR BAGS</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. FROM PRESSURE PROTECTION VALVE</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. CENTERING PIN HOLES</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. END OF ROD TO BE FLUSH WITH FLAT EDGE OF VALVE</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. CAPSCREW (TORQUE 14.75 FT-LBS.) (20 N&#8226;M)</callout1>
                    <callout1>6. CENTER PUNCH MARK TO BE TOWARD LINK END OF ROD</callout1>
                    <callout1>7. LEVER ARM IN NEUTRAL POSITION</callout1>
                    <callout1>8. RUBBER LINK</callout1>
                    <callout1>9. CLAMP</callout1>
                    <callout1>10. VERTICAL LINKAGE</callout1>
                    <callout1>11. LOWER ANCHOR</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <para>The height control valve (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0300104">Figure 4</hotlnk>) is mounted at the rear of vehicle frame. The valve has a
                lever arm connected to the rear axle assembly with a vertical linkage rod. This height control valve
                lever is sensitive to frame height thus providing automatic filling or exhausting of the air springs to
                keep the vehicle level.
            </para>
            <figure id="f0300104" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic id="g0300104" filename="../figg03/G0300104.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="514px"
                         scalefitheight="472px"/>
                <caption>Figure 4. Height Control Valve Mounting Rear Of Frame</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. VERTICAL LINKAGE</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. HEIGHT CONTROL VALVE</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. MOUNTING BRACKET</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <para>The lever arm neutral position feature (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0300103">Figure 3</hotlnk>) is also incorporated in the valve and serves to
                automatically return the valve to a closed position. The height control valve is closed in the neutral
                position.
            </para>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
